      "content": "Thanks, those are good starting points. However, some of these feel a bit surface-level for a high school debate level. For example, the economic argument and the national security point are often dismissed by the opposition as being based on fear or flawed logic. \n\nTo help my students really hold their own, can you give me more nuanced, deep-dive versions of these? Specifically, how would a sophisticated proponent frame the \"rule of law\" argument so it doesn't just sound like a talking point, but a fundamental principle of democratic stability? And can you expand on the economic side without it sounding like a simple \"protect jobs\" slogan?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
